AVIAN INFLUENZA (171): INDIA (MADHYA PRADESH) WILD BIRD, HPAI H5N8, OIE
***********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 8 Dec 2021
Source: OIE-WAHIS (World Animal Health Information System) 2021 [edited]
https://wahis.oie.int/#/report-info?reportId=44023


Highly pathogenic influenza A viruses (inf. with) (non-poultry including wild birds) (2017-), India
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Started: 28 Nov 2021
Confirmed: 29 Nov 2021
Reported: 7 Dec 2021
Reason for notification: recurrence
Last occurrence: 5 Jun 2017
Causal agent: Highly pathogenic avian influenza virus [HPAI]
Serotype: H5N8
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

Outbreak location: Urban Area (Mutton Market) Agar, Agar Malva, Madhya Pradesh
Started: 28 Nov 2021
Epidemiological unit: not applicable
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
House crow (_Corvus splendens_): Corvidae-Passeriformes / - / 8 / 8 / - / - / -

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive

Control measures at event level
Domestic control measures applied: disinfection; official disposal of carcasses, by-products, and waste; quarantine; surveillance outside containment and or the protection zone; surveillance within containment and or the protection zone

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Outbreaks / Test / Test date / Result
National Institute of High Security Animal Diseases (NIHSAD), Bhopal, India (OIE reference laboratory) / house crow / 1 / real-time reverse transcription polymerase chain reaction (rRT-PCR) / 29 Nov 2021 / positive

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[Many species of migratory waterfowl winter in India, and it is also year-round habitat for several resident waterfowl species. A recent study showed that HPAI outbreaks are strongly demarcated by wild waterfowl and their interface with domestic poultry in specific wetland habitat in India (https://doi.org/10.3390/v12111290). - Mod.PMB

ProMED map:
Agar, Madhya Pradesh, India: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8700157,56700]
